The MI350 HBM bandwidth numbers were inflated because every block assigned to the same target CC read the same pointer stream.

In the kernel, the pointer table was selected by CC/hop, then offset only by threadIdx.x:

B += threadIdx.x;

There was no blockIdx.x component. So many blocks in the same CC repeatedly touched the same B[i] / B[i + N] entries and payload addresses. On MI350, with only 2 CCs, this created strong cache/fabric reuse while the bandwidth formula still multiplied by total blockCount, as if every block generated independent HBM traffic. That is why hop0 could report impossible values like ~11.5 TB/s, above the 8.0 TB/s theoretical HBM bandwidth.

I fixed it by passing each CC pointer-table length into the kernel and adding a valid per-
block offset:

const size_t window_width = 2 * (size_t)N;
const size_t window_count = B_count > window_width ? B_count - window_width + 1 : 1;
size_t block_stride = (window_count + (size_t)gridDim.x - 1) / (size_t)gridDim.x;
...
const size_t block_offset = ((size_t)blockIdx.x * block_stride) % window_count;
B += block_offset + threadIdx.x;

I also adjusted the host-side bounds checks to account for the existing dB* += i shift, so the B + N stream stays in bounds.

MI300 had the same missing block offset. I patched MI300 the same way. It likely looked less obviously broken because MI300 has 4 CCs, spreading the shared streams across more CCs, while MI350 has 2 CCs and exposed the reuse much more strongly.

Validation on MI350 HBM-49:

old hop0: 11541.0 GB/s, 55.2% spread
new hop0:  3936.5 GB/s,  4.4% spread

old hop1:  3458.2 GB/s, 16.9% spread
new hop1:  2719.4 GB/s,  0.0% spread